  "prompt": "Who all can apply the title \"Er.\" as a prefix for their names?",
  "response": "The title \"Er.\" is commonly used as a prefix in some countries, particularly in India, to denote an engineer. It stands for \"Engineer\" and is typically used by individuals who have a degree in engineering or have been formally recognized as engineers in their field. \n\nTo apply the title \"Er.\" before their names, individuals generally need to meet the following criteria:\n\n1. **Educational Qualification**: They should have completed a degree in engineering from a recognized institution (e.g., B.E. or B.Tech).\n   \n2. **Professional Recognition**: In some cases, they might be required to be registered with a professional engineering body or council that grants the right to use the title.\n\nIn summary, anyone who holds a recognized engineering degree and practices in the engineering profession can use the title \"Er.\" before their name.",
